post_text:
PBS Teaching Tennessee- Now Available

Through a continued partnership with the state’s PBS stations, Tennessee students will have access to daily educational content all summer through the PBS Teaching Tennessee.

Starting September 8, all six Tennessee PBS stations will offer high quality educational programming weekdays from 9 a.m. –11 a.m. CT, throughout the fall semester. For the month of September and beginning of October, PBS Teaching Tennessee will feature instructional content on ELA and math for 1st- 4th grades. During the fall semester, the schedule will be updated to focus on various grades and subjects.

https://www.tn.gov/education/pbsteaching.html

September 3 at 12:48 PM ·

Celebrate Food Safety Education Month by buying a food thermometer and using it to make sure meat reaches a temperature high enough to kill germs.
✅160°F for ground meats, such as beef and pork
✅165°F for all poultry, including ground chicken and turkey
✅145°F for whole cuts of beef, pork, veal, and lamb (then let rest for 3 minutes before carving or eating)

McMinn County 2020 Census
July 13 at 11:21 AM ·

Census results shape the future of our community, as census data informs how billions of dollars in federal funds are distributed for health clinics, school lunch programs, disaster recovery initiatives, and other critical programs and services for the next 10 years.

McMinn County is currently at a 54.9% Self Response Rate. Two weeks ago on June 30, we were at 54.8%.

Please keep sharing and spreading the word amongst your neighbor and friends to participate in the 2020 Census. #McMinnCounts!

To participate, visit: my2020census.gov to begin the questionnaire.

State just announced the DEADLINE has been EXTENDED to JULY 27.

ACS Families can take advantage of this opportunity! All families qualify due to all Athens City Schools being on the CEP program. Applications deadline is July 27 tdhs.service-now.com‬
‪or call 1-833-496-0661 and select option 3.

Only current SNAP and TANF recipients could skip the application process.

As a reminder, households can login their P-EBT application to check the status of the application. If the status is “Needs Review,” the application is still being validated against eligibility data. “Needs review” means a determination has not been made yet, and it does not necessarily mean benefits will be denied. For those who applied when the application first opened, the 14-day response time on their notification has passed, but it doesn’t mean benefits have been denied or that they have been forgotten. The applications are simply still under review.

They will start issuing cards mid-July unless there are current SNAP and TANF recipients. Cards will arrive in the mail

shared_text:
McMinn County Mayor John Gentry
April 27 at 6:37 PM ·

As many of you know, McMinn County’s COVID-19 count spiked over the last two days as a result of the situation at Lifecare Center of Athens. While the Tennessee Department of Health is the lead agency in assisting Lifecare in the response to the outbreak at their facility, I have been in contact with the local executive director to assure him that McMinn County Government is here to help if he needs our assistance. Lifecare and Starr Regional Medical Center are also in close contact in the event that Lifecare patients are in need of higher level medical care.

As we begin the phased reopening of the economy, it is extremely important to continue to take necessary precautions and follow the state's recently released guidance when doing business at restaurants and retail establishments.

McMinn County Mayor John Gentry is at McMinn County Health Department.
April 11 at 4:32 PM · Athens, TN ·

McMinn COVID-19 Update
Saturday, April 11, 2020

Testing at the McMinn County Health Department this weekend was an amazing success with our site generating the largest participation per capita in southeast Tennessee! The state has extended free testing into next week at the McMinn County Health Department where it will take place each day from 9 a.m. until noon. Anyone is welcome to receive a test. It is not required to be referred by a physician, and one does not have to be exhibiting symptoms.

McMinn County now has four confirmed cases, but we also have confirmed that three of those patients have fully recovered. To only have one active case at this point is truly a blessing, so continue to be safe and social distance as we flatten the curve!

If you or someone you know is struggling, help is available. Learn more at www.tnfacesofopioids.com

shared_text:
WJSQ WLAR
April 3 at 1:52 PM ·

Athens Parks and Recreation limits park usage to comply with Governor’s Orders and CDC guidelines

Effective immediately the City of Athens will close all public restrooms, be removing basketball rims, volleyball nets, and soccer goals in the park system.

The skatepark at the Ingleside Recreation Complex will be closed and two nets from each set of tennis courts will be removed. Courts will be limited to two players on each court.

Playgrounds at all areas will continue to be closed and no organized group activities are permitted.

Citizens are not to enter any area designated as closed.

Additionally, until further notice, park operating hours at all locations will be 7am until 9pm.

The intent of this action is to allow open spaces to be used while following the Governor’s orders and the CDC social distancing guidelines.

For more information, please contact the Office of Parks & Recreation at (423) 744-2700 EXT 3.

February 26 at 12:44 PM ·

This is Severe Weather Awareness Week. Today's focus is on tornado safety. Here are a few tips from TEMA: Know where to take shelter during a #tornado:
1.Tornado storm shelters or safe rooms are best.
2. Basements & interior rooms are also good.
3. Vehicles are not safe.
4. Shed, storage facilities & highway overpasses are not safe.
http://weather.gov/safety/tornado-during #SWAW

County Center for Excellence
Adult Education Office
Niota Depot
City Hall, Englewood (formerly at Wilson Drugs, Englewood)
Calhoun Elementary School
Etowah Depot

Westside Elementary
November 21, 2019 at 12:20 PM ·

Westside students collected over $900 for Relay for Life in a coin feud between the houses. Onesta was the winning house and will celebrate with an ice cream party.

shared_text:
Westside Elementary
November 22, 2019 at 5:01 PM ·

Westside students came out strong today to support Neyland Pickel. With hat day and Kickball championships the students raised over $900 for Neyland and his family. TEAM Neyland from TWU showed up to play the championship team. The highlight of the day was to see Neyland's face playing with TWU baseball players. Thank you to all parents, students, teachers, and TWU Baseball for making today wonderful for Neyland. #TEAMNEYLAND #TennesseeWesleyanathletics
